{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χαλεπ-ός</b>, ή, όν, <br /> <b>difficult</b> (ὃ ἂν μὴ ῥᾴδιον ᾖ ἀλλὰ διὰ πολλῶν πραγμάτων γίγνηται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 341d: opposed to ῥᾴδιος, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1363a24, in various relations): \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> in reference to the feelings, <b>hard to bear, painful, grievous</b> (so frequently in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus), κεραυνός 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.417; θύελλα 21.335; ἄνεμοι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.286; πόνος 23.250; ἄλγος, πένθος, 2.193, 6.169; γῆρας 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.103; ἄλη 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.464; χαλεπώτερος ἄεθλος 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 800 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἄλλα τῶν κατεχόντων πρηγμάτων - ώτερα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.40; χ. πνεῦμα 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 166 (Lyric poetry); δύα [prev. author] “Th.” 228 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαλεπώτατα [πράγματα] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1273 (_anapaest meter_); συμφορά 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 768 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; νόσος, πλάνη, etc., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Symposium” 4.37, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 245e (_comparative_), etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ ἐσβολὴ αὕτη -ωτάτη τοῖς Ἀθηναίοις ἐγένετο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.26 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; [θώρακες] δύσφοροι καὶ χ., of ill-fitting cuirasses, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 3.10.13: τὸ χ. τοῦ πνεύματος\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] the <b>severity</b> of the wind, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “An.” 4.5.4 \">Refs</a>]; τὰ χ. <b>hardships,</b> opposed to τὰ τερπνά, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Mem.” 2.1.23, etc.; τερπνῶν χαλεπῶν τε κρίσις 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 131, compare 3rd c.AD: Plotinus Philosophus 5.9.14 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>comparative</i>, <b>more unpleasant,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator “Orationes” 6.202c. \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3> <b>hard to do</b> or <b>deal with, difficult, irksome,</b> -ώτατον ἔργον ἁπάντων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 516 (_anapaest meter_); compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.59 (_superlative_), etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαλεπὰ τὰ καλά proverbial cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Hp.Ma.” 304e, +others\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], attributed to Solon by Scholia (at [prev. work]); χαλεπὸν ὁ βίος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.9.1, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Politicus” 299e: with \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i> <i>active</i> or <i>middle</i>, χαλεπή τοι ἐγὼ μένος ἀντιφέρεσθαι, = {χαλεπόν ἐστί μοι ἀντιφέρεσθαί σοι}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.482; χαλεποὶ δὲ θεοὶ φαίνεσθαι ἐναργεῖς 20.131 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χαλεπὸν δέ τ᾽ ὀρύσσειν [τὸ μῶλυ] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.305; χ. προϊδέσθαι καπρός 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 386; χ. ἔρις ἀνθρώποις ὁμιλεῖν κρεσσόνων 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 10.72; χ. προσπολεμεῖν 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 4.138, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.51 (_comparative_)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χ. συγγενέσθαι, εὑρεῖν, γενέσθαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 330c, 412b, 502c; χ. πάσχειν [prev. author] “Cri.” 49b (_comparative_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: also with <i>infinitive</i> <i>passive</i>, χαλεπὸς διαγνωσθῆναι καὶ δειχθῆναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 2.1.1, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.94, etc.; χαλεπὸν ληφθῆναι ὁ τόπος 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Physica” 212a8 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαλεπόν [ἐστι] with <i>infinitive</i>, 'tis <b>hard, difficult</b> to do, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.651 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; with <i>accusative</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, 'tis <b>difficult for</b> one to do.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.620, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 20.313 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>dative</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.184, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.156. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.3</b></Level3> <b>dangerous,</b> λιμένες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 19.189; θάλασσα 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.24; χ. τὰ παρόντα 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 3.2.2. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.4</b></Level3> of ground, <b>difficult, rugged,</b> χωρία χ. καὶ πετρώδη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.9; ὁδός [prev. author] 5.58, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 328e; χ... καὶ προσάντης.. ὁδός ἐστιν 4th c.BC: Anaxandrides Comicus 56; πρόσοδοι 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 5.2.3; πορεία [prev. work] 5.6.10; σταθμός [prev. work] 4.5.3 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χωρίον -ώτατον a place <b>most difficult to take,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 4.8.2. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> of persons, <b>hard to deal with, cruel, harsh, stern</b> (opposed to πρᾷος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 493b (_superlative_), 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1126a26), βασιλεύς, δαίμων, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.232, 19.201; χαλεποί τε καὶ ἄγριοι 8.575 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <b>-ώτερος</b> <b>a more bitter enemy,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.40 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; -ώτατοι <b>most difficult to deal with, most dangerous</b> or <b>troublesome,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 42, compare 7.21; -ώτεροι πάροικοι [prev. author] 3.113; χαλεπόν γε θυγάτηρ κτῆμα 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 18 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>dative</i> <i>person</i>, <b>cruel</b> or <b>harsh</b> towards one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.388; τοῖς ξυμπροθυμηθεῖσι τὸν ἔκπλουν 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.1, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς τοὺς πολεμίους, τοὺς ἀγνῶτας, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 375c, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1328a8 (also πρὸς τοὺς δρόμους 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Cynegeticus” 5.17); ἐπὶ νύμφαις ἀλλοτρίαις 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 22.145. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.b</b></Level4> of words, χαλεπῷ ἠνίπαπε μύθῳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.245, etc.; ἐρεθιζέμεν αἰεὶ μύθοισιν χ. 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.395 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χ. ὀνείδεα, ὁμοκλαί, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 3.438, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.189; φῆμις 14.239; μῆνις 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.178. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.c</b></Level4> especially of judges, ἦν τὸ δίκαιον φυλάσσων χ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.100, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Critias” 107d, 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 4.36; also χ. ἀρχή 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.77; τιμωρία 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 39c (_comparative_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; νόμοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Hp.Mi.” 372a (_comparative_), 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.44, 35.50. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.d</b></Level4> <b>savage, fierce,</b> κύνες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 5.8.24, “Cyn.” 10.23 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of bees, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 624b30 (_comparative_)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; [θηρία] χ. τὰς φύσεις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Politicus” 274b. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>ill-tempered, testy,</b> χ. ὢν καὶ δύσκολος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 942, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 19.26; ὀργὴν χ. 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.131 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαλεπῇ τῇ χειρί with a <b>rough</b> hand, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 1116. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> of plants, <b>hurtful to the soil,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 8.9.3 (_superlative_). \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> <i>adverb</i> -πῶς <b>hardly, with difficulty,</b> διαγνῶναι χ. ἦν ἄνδρα ἕκαστον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.424; χ. δέ σ᾽ ἔολπα τὸ ῥέξειν 20.186; χ. κε φύγοις κακόν 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 684; χ. ὀργὰς μεταβάλλουσιν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 121 (_anapaest meter_); χ. γνῶναι 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 3.2.1; τὰ τοῖς ἄλλοις χ. εὑρημένα ῥᾳδίως μανθάνειν 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 1.18, compare 44\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] οὐ or μὴ χ. without <b>much ado,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.2, 7.81, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.2</b></Level3> <b>hardly, scarcely,</b> δοκέω.. χ. ἂν Ἕλληνας Πέρσῃσι μάχεσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.103; χ. παρὰ τοῖς ἐχθροῖς εὑρεθήσεται 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 29.2; χ. ἂν πείσαιμι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 84d. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.3</b></Level3> χ. ἔχει, ={χαλεπόν ἐστι}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.53 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>accusative</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 7.4.6. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.4</b></Level3> <b>painfully, miserably,</b> -ώτερον ζῆν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 579d; ἐν τοῖς -ώτατα διῆγον 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.71. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.II</b></Level2> of persons, <b>angrily, cruelly, harshly,</b> χ. τιμωρεῖσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 3.46; ἀποκρίνασθαι [prev. author] 5.42, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 203 (_anapaest meter_), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 60, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 269b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χ. φέρειν τι take it <b>ill,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.16, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 330a, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also χ. ἔφερον τῷ πολέμῳ, τοῖς πράγμασιν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 5.1.29, “An.” 1.3.3; ἐπὶ τῇ πολιορκίᾳ [prev. author] “HG” 7.4.21, compare 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 3.50; also χ. φέρειν τινός 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.62; also χ. λαμβάνεσθαι τοῦ παιδός 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.121. ; χ. λαμβάνειν περί τινος 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 6.61 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of the laws [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare(above 11.1c), χ. προστάττειν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 925d. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.2</b></Level3> frequently in the phrase χ. ἔχειν to be <b>angry,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 6.4.16, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τινι <b>with</b> one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “HG” 1.5.16; πρὸς τοὺς λόγους 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 3.3, compare 51\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] χ. ἔχειν τισὶν ἐπί τινι <b>with</b> persons for a thing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 20.135, compare 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Cicero” 43; χ. διακεῖσθαι πρὸς ἅπαντας 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator “Epistulae” 7.5; χ. πρὸς φιλοσοφίαν διακεῖσθαι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 500b; χ. πρὸς ἡμᾶς διετέθησαν 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 8.79; ἐπί τινι χ. διατεθείς 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Pericles” 36. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__B.II.2.b</b></Level4> χ. ἔχειν, also, to be <b>in a bad way,</b> χ. ἔχω ὑπὸ τοῦ πότου [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 176a, compare “Tht.” 142b.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]— Beside the regular <i>comparative</i> χαλεπώτερον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"(5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.77, 7.50, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 94d, etc.)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] we have <b>-ωτέρως</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.50, 8.40, 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Historia Plantarum” 6.7.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>superlative</i> <b>-ώτατα</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.71, 8.95, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 579d, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5467","accentedUnicode":"χαλεπός","shortDef":"difficult, harsh; violent","mediumDef":"difficult, harsh; violent <br /><b>hard, rugged; furious, ferocious, violent</b> <ref='Mat.8.28'>Mt. 8:28</ref>; <b>difficult, trying, harsh</b> <ref='2Ti.3.1'>2Tim. 3:1</ref>*","stepGloss":"harsh","stepTransliteration":"chalepos","count":2,"_es_Definition":"duro, trabajoso, difícil, lleno de dificultades ; violento, feroz (de hombres)","_zh_tw_Definition":"艱困的 (太 8:28; 提後 3:1)","_zh_Definition":"艰困的 (太 8:28; 提后 3:1)","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"khó chịu; hung dữ; khó khăn.","_zh_tw_Gloss":"兇猛","_es_Gloss":"duro","_zh_Gloss":"凶猛"}]}